Q1: Total amount per user

SELECT user_id, SUM(amount) AS total_amount
FROM transactions
GROUP BY user_id;

Q2: Users whose total transaction amount > 1000

SELECT user_id, SUM(amount) AS total_amount
FROM transactions
GROUP BY user_id
HAVING total_amount > 1000;

Q3: Number of SUCCESS transactions per user

SELECT user_id, COUNT(*) AS success_count
FROM transactions
WHERE status = 'SUCCESS'
GROUP BY user_id;

Q4: Users with more than 2 transactions

SELECT user_id, COUNT(*) AS txn_count
FROM transactions
GROUP BY user_id
HAVING txn_count > 2;

#Wrong Query

SELECT user_id, COUNT(*)
FROM transactions
WHERE COUNT(*) > 2
GROUP BY user_id;

#Why this fails?

-WHERE runs before grouping
- But COUNT(*) is calculated after grouping

## Why can't we use aggregate functions in WHERE?
Because:
WHERE executes before GROUP BY
Aggregate functions (SUM, COUNT) are calculated after GROUP BY

So they don’t exist yet during WHERE.

Why HAVING exists? HAVING is used to:
-Filter grouped data
-Work with aggregate functions

## Simple Way to Remember
WHERE → row-level filtering
HAVING → group-level filtering




